{
"response_text": "The number of households engaged in social learning starts at zero and increases steadily over the course of the simulation. This initial rise begins around the 7th time step, indicating the early adoption of social information sharing among the agents. The metric climbs to reach a peak value of approximately 32 households at time step 63. Throughout the growth phase, there are periods of fluctuation, particularly between time steps 22 and 32 and again from 51 to 59, which may reflect varying degrees of agent susceptibility to social influence or changes in environmental uncertainty. A shift in the trend dynamics occurs at time step 40, yet the overall direction remains positive. By the end of the simulation at time step 100, the value stabilizes at approximately 32 households.\n\nThis pattern suggests that social learning behavior diffuses through the population over time, starting from no engagement to a stable state where a significant portion of the households rely on observing neighbors. The plateau indicates that the strategy has been widely adopted among those capable of engaging in this behavior, likely driven by the benefits of reducing uncertainty in livestock management decisions under variable rainfall conditions. The oscillations during the growth phase likely reflect the heterogeneity in agent risk attitudes and the stochastic nature of the resource system, influencing the perceived value of social information at different stages of the common property grazing cycle."
}

